  "text": "Specimens of Eualetes tulipa from the Royapuram fishing harbour were attached to the substrate by tightly coiled whorls, while the lax distal part of the shell, referred to as the feeding tube, grows quite large [CITATION_1] . The lengths of the shell varied from 5 to 9 cm, 1 to 1.5 cm in width. Shell colours varied from ivory white to light brown and dark grey. The inner surface of the shell is smooth, with light brown coloration. The elongated and worm-shaped soft body, of a pale red-wine colour (Figure 4) , measured from 5.0 to 7.2 cm (maximum recorded length reported elsewhere: 14.1 cm; Miloslavich and Penchaszadeh 1992). The brown concave operculum, marked with several whorls, measures around 0.5 cm in diameter.",
